Ask HN: How do you deal with a super hero team leader?
text:
Got on a new company, great spirit and business but the team manager likes to be the super hero for the business: he blocks all team communication with other teams, only he knows what to do next and only what he does or his solutions are correct.

Sometimes we have a roadmap and processes but he is the first one to not follow them (he approves his own PRs and sometimes develop in production ).

The consequences are obvious regarding and overall the team is demotivated.

I've been trying to go around by having conversations with him suggesting new approaches to stuff just for him to present them as his ideas on the next week. I don't really mind that but it's managing him that is completely draining me.

Any suggestions on how to approach this? I do love the company and the business teams but this is not sustainable for the next months.

Ask HN: I just heard a radio ad for Tinder. Is this weird?
text: So I’m currently sat in my barbers and I just heard a radio ad on Kiss FM for Tinder. I can’t ever remember hearing a radio ad for an app company. Maybe a legacy company that has made an app. But not an established tech company like Tinder. Maybe I just don’t catch much radio in the age of streaming but yeah, strikes me as jarring and odd. HN thoughts?

Show HN: Cataclysm v0.1 – the final Python module?
text:
cataclysm is an over-the-top experiment to take more of the human out of coding. I haven't taught it to use itself yet if a module isn't installed, but that's next on the agenda once GPT4 isn't so slow.

Video intro here: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ZK8fUuQDgZ4

Fun experiment: I fed it some of the 'tests' for other simple Python based modules and it was pretty good at implementing what was needed to succeed at them by replacing their module name with `doom.`. Obviously lots it can't do, but it's already surprisingly reliable.

You'll need a GPT4 API key-- it works with ChatGPT 3.5 turbo but that code is a little less reliable (and it can't generate as lengthy code).

It has two modes-- the ridiculous 'global' cataclysm mode for use in notebooks/interpreter that lets you hand-wave any function name and it'll cook it up for you. This is a bit scary (a typo turns into random code execution), so the second mode is just to use 'doom.' in front of any function name and it'll generate/cache its best guess for the right code given where it's called in the call stack (and its name/types/parameter names/etc).

A bit extreme, but a small concept to help us adjust to the impending cataclysm ahead of us. :)
